[2] South Africa (Gauteng)
Date: Thu 11 Dec 2014
Source: The Citizen, Caxton News Service report [edited]
http://citizen.co.za/291436/5-provinces-including-gauteng-hit-measles-outbreak/


There has been an increase in laboratory-confirmed measles cases in Gauteng and 4 other provinces. The National Institute for Communicable Diseases said the Northern Cape [province] has reported the highest increase with 5 laboratory-confirmed measles cases detected within a 4-week period in the Siyanda District Municipality.

The Northern Cape health department [NICD] has reportedly initiated an investigation in the Siyanda District Municipality and was taking steps to help curb the outbreak. The NICD advised parents to look out for fevers rising over 3 days, a runny nose, dry cough and eyes that have turned red and become sensitive to light. Children should be taken to a clinic as soon as parents suspect that they might have contracted measles, the NICD added.

In Gauteng, there have been more than 400 confirmed cases of measles since March 2009, according to the provincial health department. In October 2009, the department embarked on a massive measles immunisation campaign in response to the confirmed cases in the province. This campaign was reportedly aimed at targeting children from the ages of 6 months up to both primary and high schools learners. Health workers visited clinics, schools and creches throughout the province for immunisation.

Measles is a highly contagious but less lethal viral disease that spreads through droplets of saliva and secretions from the nose, the department said. Last year [2013], the department immunised most children during the 1st round of a measles and polio campaign which ran from 29 Apr to 17 May 2014. The province exceeded the target of the number of children who received measles vaccine and reached 102 percent, said the department.

[Byline: Thabang Kuaho]

