[3] USA (Michigan / CDC statement)
Date: Thu 11 Dec 2014
Source: MINEWS26 [edited]
http://www.minews26.com/content/?p=35617


Following the recent confirmation of several measles cases in the Traverse City area, the Michigan Department of Community Health is reminding residents across the state to protect themselves against the disease by ensuring they're up to date on their vaccines.

Michigan is now among 23 states that have reported cases of measles this year [2014]. Two Michigan cases were unvaccinated, with the patients exposed to measles during travel in the Philippines. The other 3 involved unvaccinated residents coming into contact with the people who had contracted the disease while traveling.

From 2001-2012, the average number of measles cases reported nationally each year was 60. According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, there have been more than 600 cases reported this year [2014] in the US, and the vast majority of cases have been among people who had no history of vaccination against measles.

The Philippines is experiencing a large and ongoing measles outbreak, with more than 50 000 measles cases and more than 100 measles-related deaths reported this year [2014]. Many of the cases in the U.S. this year have been traced to travel in or contact with the Philippines.

Measles is a disease that can result in hospitalization, pneumonia, and death. Because measles is highly contagious, successful prevention and control require high levels of immunity in all communities. The disease is preventable by simply being vaccinated.

[Byline: Eric Wotila]

