[4] USA (Michigan / Grand Traverse & Leeland)
Date: Thu 11 Dec 2014
Source: MILIVE.com [abridged, edited]
http://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2014/12/post_557.html


There are now 5 confirmed cases of measles in Grand Traverse and Leeland counties, health officials reported on Wed 10 Dec 2014.

On Thu 4 Dec 2014, the Grand Traverse County Health Department reported there were 2 adult cases in the county involving unimmunized people who recently had returned from the Philippines. The 3 new cases involve an adult and 2 children, all not immunized, from Leeland County. They had contact with the Grand Traverse adults. "The children did not attend school during the infectious period," according to the joint press release from the Grand Traverse and Benzie-Leeland health department, who are not releasing the name of the school.

Nearly 45 percent of Michigan residents now live in counties at risk of disease outbreaks, according to an MLive analysis of state data. Michigan has one of the highest vaccine-waiver rates for kindergartners in the country, 3 times the national median, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

After the 1st 2 cases last week, health officials sent out an urgent message for people to get vaccinated. Dr. Michael Collins, chief medical officer for the county health department, described the disease as extraordinarily contagious with the potential to cause serious complications, even death. Several others who were exposed to the 1st adults with measles and are not immunized are being actively monitored for development of symptoms and isolated in their homes for 21 days. Those having contacts with the Leeland cases are also being investigated to determine vaccinated or immunity status and are being isolated as well. "The situation is a fluid one, but at this time, there is no indication that anyone, in any age group, was in any of the school buildings during their infectious periods. If there is a case within a school, all unimmunized children will need to be excluded from that school for many days (21 days from the last case appearing in the school)."

The 1st 2 people affected by measles are 19 and 22 years old. They returned on 17 Nov 2014 from a trip to the Philippines, where there is a major measles outbreak. They were hospitalized with measles on 26 Nov 2014 but have recovered and been discharged from the hospital, according to Dr. Collins.

